{"title_page": "Pedro Antonio Valdes-Sosa", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name              = Pedro Antonio Valdes-Sosa MD. PhD. DSc. \n| image             = Vice Director Centro de Neurociencias de Cuba.JPG\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1950|03|12}}\n| birth_place       = [[Chicago, Illinois]], USA\n| nationality       = Cuban\n}}\n\n'''Pedro Antonio Valdes-Sosa''' (born March 12, 1950 in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States]]), is the General Vice-Director for Research of the [[Cuban Neurosciences Center]], which he cofounded in 1990. He is also Member of the Editorial Boards of the following journals: Neuroimage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://journals.elsevier.com/10538119/neuroimage/ |title=NeuroImage |publisher=Journals.elsevier.com |date=2011-04-30 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> Medicc,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicc.org/ns/ |title=Welcome to MEDICC |publisher=Medicc.org |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref>   Audiology and Neurotology,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.karger.com/ProdukteDB/produkte.asp?Aktion=JournalHome&ProduktNr=224213&ContentOnly=false |title=Audiology and Neurotology |publisher=Content.karger.com |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> PLosOne<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plosone.org/home.action |title=accelerating the publication of peer-reviewed science |publisher=PLoS ONE |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> Frontiers, Neuroimage and Brain Connectivity. His work includes statistical analysis of electrophysiological measurements, neuroimaging ([[fMRI]], [[EEG]] and MEG tomography), nonlinear dynamical modeling of brain functions and Software and electrophysiological equipment development.\n\nValdes-Sosa initiated work with quantitative electrophysiology in 1969 with the first Cuban microcomputer, co-founding CNEURO in 1990, an institution which has changed health indicators in his country as well as in others. His research includes (computational) theory, methodology, and both fMRI and electromagnetic brain imaging, with contributions to multichannel EEG/MEG (1969\u20131989), Distributed ESI (Electrophysiological Source Imaging, 1989), SPM for ESI (2000), [[Granger Causality]] (1998). Neural mass modeling (1997), and EEG/fMRI fusion (2001). He has been active in promoting Brain Mapping, setting up international collaborations and societies, the Cuban and Latin-American Brain Mapping projects, participating actively in OHBM since 1998, having served on its Program Committee.\n\n==Academic biography==\n[[File:Pedro Antonio Valdes-Sosa 02.jpg|thumb|left|Prof. Pedro Antonio Vald\u00e9s-Sosa in a talk at the Research, Innovation and Dissemination Center for Neuromathematics (NeuroMat), in S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil, in March, 2015.]]\nDr. Valdes-Sosa studied medicine at the [[University of Havana]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.cu/ |title=Universidad de La Habana |publisher=Uh.cu |accessdate=2011-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041103085342/http://www.uh.cu/ |archivedate=2004-11-03 }}</ref> and graduated in 1972. He also studied Mathematics in 1973. He obtained his Ph.D. in 1978 . In 1979 he realized a postdoc training on \"Neurometrics and Computational Techniques\" and \u201cBiophysical Modeling of brain electrical activity\u201d with Prof. E. Roy John at the Brain Research Lab of New York University USA. In 2011 obtained his Doctor in Science degree.\n\nHe is a senior professor of the Higher Institute for Medical Sciences, full member of the [[Cuban Academy of Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academiaciencias.cu/English/indexen.asp |title=Cuba's Sciences Academy |publisher=Academiaciencias.cu |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> full member of the [[Latin American Academy of Sciences]], associate member of the International Center for Theoretical Physics. He has also been invited professor of the Institute of Statistical Mathematics of Japan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ism.ac.jp/index_e.html |title=The Institute of Statistical Mathematics |publisher=Ism.ac.jp |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> invited researcher of the Brain Science Institute of RIKEN, Japan and Honorary Professor of UCL. 2010 Head of Overseas Team of Talent Introducing Base for Neuroinformation (111 Project) China. 2011 Visiting Professor for Senior International Scientific of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.\n\nIn addition, he has been Ph.D. advisor of 14 doctoral students. At present he is Distinguished Professor of Neuroinformatics of the Key Laboratory for Neuroinformation, [[University of Electronic Science and Technology of China]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oice.uestc.edu.cn/en/|title=University of Electronic Science and Technology of China|publisher=uestc.edu.cn|date= |accessdate=2013-12-06 }}</ref> and Program Chair of the [[Organization for Human Brain Mapping]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanbrainmapping.org|title=Organization for Human Brain Mapping|publisher=humanbrainmapping.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 1997 Valdes-Sosa received the [[Cuban Academy of Science]] Award .Statistic Tridimensional Mapping of the EEG Generator's Spectra. In 1995 he received the \u201cCarlos J. Finlay\u201d Award for Scientific Achievements. In 2006 he was got the \u201cJos\u00e9 Tey\u201d Award for his dedication to the Education of other professionals. In 2007, he received a Ministry of Science, Technology and Environment Special Award and the Cuban Academy of Science Award both in recognition of the scientific research work: Determination of  functional networks in the brain through Granger's causality. In 2013 he received the Award to the best Doctorate Thesis in 2012 of the Academy of Sciences and Ministry of Higher Education of Cuba \u201cGranger causality on the determination of brain functional networks\u201d.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==Grants==\n* 1998/2000  Human Science Frontier Program HSFP \"Oscillations and brain\"\n* 2004  United Nations Program for Development UNDP\n* 2006 Grant from the Council on Early Child Development of Canada\n* 2010-2014 Atlantic Philanthropies<ref>{{Cite web|title = Cuban Neuroscience Center (CNEURO)|url = http://www.atlanticphilanthropies.org/grantee/cuban-neuroscience-center-cneuro|website = Atlantic Philanthropies|accessdate = 2015-06-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=0M2PVJIAAAAJ List of publications], Google Scholar\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valdes-Sosa, Pedro Antonio}}\n[[Category:Cuban scientists]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name              = Pedro Antonio Valdes-Sosa MD. PhD. DSc. \n| image             = Vice Director Centro de Neurociencias de Cuba.JPG\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1950|03|12}}\n| birth_place       = [[Chicago, Illinois]], USA\n| nationality       = Cuban\n}}\n\n'''Pedro Antonio Valdes-Sosa''' (born March 12, 1950 in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States]]), is the General Vice-Director for Research of the [[Cuban Neurosciences Center]], which he cofounded in 1990. He is also Member of the Editorial Boards of the following journals: Neuroimage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://journals.elsevier.com/10538119/neuroimage/ |title=NeuroImage |publisher=Journals.elsevier.com |date=2011-04-30 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> Medicc,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicc.org/ns/ |title=Welcome to MEDICC |publisher=Medicc.org |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref>   Audiology and Neurotology,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.karger.com/ProdukteDB/produkte.asp?Aktion=JournalHome&ProduktNr=224213&ContentOnly=false |title=Audiology and Neurotology |publisher=Content.karger.com |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> PLosOne<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plosone.org/home.action |title=accelerating the publication of peer-reviewed science |publisher=PLoS ONE |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> Frontiers, Neuroimage and Brain Connectivity. His work includes statistical analysis of electrophysiological measurements, neuroimaging ([[fMRI]], [[EEG]] and MEG tomography), nonlinear dynamical modeling of brain functions and Software and electrophysiological equipment development.\n\nValdes-Sosa initiated work with quantitative electrophysiology in 1969 with the first Cuban microcomputer, co-founding CNEURO in 1990, an institution which has changed health indicators in his country as well as in others. His research includes (computational) theory, methodology, and both fMRI and electromagnetic brain imaging, with contributions to multichannel EEG/MEG (1969\u20131989), Distributed ESI (Electrophysiological Source Imaging, 1989), SPM for ESI (2000), [[Granger Causality]] (1998). Neural mass modeling (1997), and EEG/fMRI fusion (2001). He has been active in promoting Brain Mapping, setting up international collaborations and societies, the Cuban and Latin-American Brain Mapping projects, participating actively in OHBM since 1998, having served on its Program Committee.\n\n==Academic biography==\n[[File:Pedro Antonio Valdes-Sosa 02.jpg|thumb|left|Prof. Pedro Antonio Vald\u00e9s-Sosa in a talk at the Research, Innovation and Dissemination Center for Neuromathematics (NeuroMat), in S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil, in March, 2015.]]\nDr. Valdes-Sosa studied medicine at the [[University of Havana]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.cu/ |title=Universidad de La Habana |publisher=Uh.cu |accessdate=2011-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041103085342/http://www.uh.cu/ |archivedate=2004-11-03 }}</ref> and graduated in 1972. He also studied Mathematics in 1973. He obtained his Ph.D. in 1978 . In 1979 he realized a postdoc training on \"Neurometrics and Computational Techniques\" and \u201cBiophysical Modeling of brain electrical activity\u201d with Prof. E. Roy John at the Brain Research Lab of New York University USA. In 2011 obtained his Doctor in Science degree.\n\nHe is a senior professor of the Higher Institute for Medical Sciences, full member of the [[Cuban Academy of Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academiaciencias.cu/English/indexen.asp |title=Cuba's Sciences Academy |publisher=Academiaciencias.cu |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> full member of the [[Latin American Academy of Sciences]], associate member of the International Center for Theoretical Physics. He has also been invited professor of the Institute of Statistical Mathematics of Japan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ism.ac.jp/index_e.html |title=The Institute of Statistical Mathematics |publisher=Ism.ac.jp |date= |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> invited researcher of the Brain Science Institute of RIKEN, Japan and Honorary Professor of UCL. 2010 Head of Overseas Team of Talent Introducing Base for Neuroinformation (111 Project) China. 2011 Visiting Professor for Senior International Scientific of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.\n\nIn addition, he has been Ph.D. advisor of 14 doctoral students. At present he is Distinguished Professor of Neuroinformatics of the Key Laboratory for Neuroinformation, [[University of Electronic Science and Technology of China]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oice.uestc.edu.cn/en/|title=University of Electronic Science and Technology of China|publisher=uestc.edu.cn|date= |accessdate=2013-12-06 }}</ref> and Program Chair of the [[Organization for Human Brain Mapping]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanbrainmapping.org|title=Organization for Human Brain Mapping|publisher=humanbrainmapping.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 1997 Valdes-Sosa received the [[Cuban Academy of Science]] Award .Statistic Tridimensional Mapping of the EEG Generator\u2019s Spectra. In 1995 he received the \u201cCarlos J. Finlay\u201d Award for Scientific Achievements. In 2006 he was got the \u201cJos\u00e9 Tey\u201d Award for his dedication to the Education of other professionals. In 2007, he received a Ministry of Science, Technology and Environment Special Award and the Cuban Academy of Science Award both in recognition of the scientific research work: Determination of  functional networks in the brain through Granger's causality. In 2013 he received the Award to the best Doctorate Thesis in 2012 of the Academy of Sciences and Ministry of Higher Education of Cuba \u201cGranger causality on the determination of brain functional networks\u201d.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==Grants==\n* 1998/2000  Human Science Frontier Program HSFP \"Oscillations and brain\"\n* 2004  United Nations Program for Development UNDP\n* 2006 Grant from the Council on Early Child Development of Canada\n* 2010-2014 Atlantic Philanthropies<ref>{{Cite web|title = Cuban Neuroscience Center (CNEURO)|url = http://www.atlanticphilanthropies.org/grantee/cuban-neuroscience-center-cneuro|website = Atlantic Philanthropies|accessdate = 2015-06-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=0M2PVJIAAAAJ List of publications], Google Scholar\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valdes-Sosa, Pedro Antonio}}\n[[Category:Cuban scientists]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards and honors:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedro_Antonio_Valdes-Sosa"}
{"title_page": "Eric Topol", "text_new": "{{infobox scientist/Wikidata\n|fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n\n'''Eric Jeffrey Topol''' (born 1954) is an American [[cardiology|cardiologist]], [[geneticist]], author, and scientist. \nHe is the Founder and Director of the Scripps Research Translational Institute<ref name=\"STSI website\">[http://www.stsiweb.org Scripps Translational Science Institute]</ref> in La Jolla, California. He also serves as the Chief Academic Officer for Scripps Health, a Professor of Genomics at [[The Scripps Research Institute]], and a Senior Consultant at the Division of Cardiovascular Diseases at Scripps Clinic. He is editor-in-chief of [[Medscape]] and ''theheart.org''. He has published 3 bestseller books on the future of medicine. His most recent book ''Deep Medicine: How Artificial Intelligence Can Make Healthcare Human Again'' came out in 2019, which focuses on how AI empowers physicians and revolutionizes the health care industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hachettebookgroup.com/titles/eric-topol/deep-medicine/9781541644632/|title=Deep Medicine|publisher=Hachette Book Group|accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref>''The Creative Destruction of Medicine'' which examined the impact of both the genomic and wireless revolutions on the health care system.  His book ''The Patient Will See You Now'', published in 2015, explores how smartphones, big data, and technology are combining to democratize health care. In 2016, Topol co-founded<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-smart-medicine-solution-to-the-health-care-crisis-1499443449|title=The Smart-Medicine Solution to the Health-Care Crisis|last=Topol|first=Eric|date=2017-07-07|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2017-07-08|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> a company developing an individual-centric health data platform. \n\nIn 2016, Topol was awarded a $207M grant from the [[National Institutes of Health]] to lead a significant part of the [[Precision Medicine Initiative]], a one million American prospective research program.<ref>{{cite web |last=Comstock |first=Jonah |date=6 October 2016 |title=NIH expands grant for Scripps-led Precision Medicine group to $207M |website=MobiHealthNews |publisher=HIMSS Media |url=http://www.mobihealthnews.com/content/nih-expands-grant-scripps-led-precision-medicine-group-207m }}</ref>\n\n== Research and training ==\nTopol's research career has been in two major areas: clinical development of new drugs and devices and genomics. Topol pioneered the development of many medications that are routinely used in medical practice including [[T-pa|t-PA]], [[Plavix]], [[Angiomax]], and [[Reopro|ReoPro]]. He has led worldwide clinical trials in over 40 countries involving over 200,000 patients (First in series \u2013 GUSTO trials).<ref name=\"GUSTO-1993-1\">{{cite journal | author=The GUSTO investigators | title=An international randomized trial comparing four thrombolytic strategies for acute myocardial infarction. The GUSTO investigators | journal=New England Journal of Medicine | year=1993 | volume=329 | issue=10 | pages=673\u201382 | pmid=8204123 | doi=10.1056/NEJM199309023291001| hdl=1765/5468 | url=http://repub.eur.nl/pub/5468 }}</ref> His work in the genomics of heart attack has led to discovery of key genes ([[Myocyte-specific enhancer factor 2A|MEF2A]] deletion, [[Thrombospondin]] variants) which led to recognition by the American Heart Association top 10 research advances in 2001 and 2003.<ref name=\"Thrombospondin Topol et al\"/><ref name=\"MEF2A-2003-Science\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wang L, Fan C, Topol SE, Topol EJ, Wang Q | title=Mutation of MEF2A in an Inherited Disorder with Features of Coronary Artery Disease | journal=Science | year=2003 | volume=302 | issue=5650 | pages=1578\u201381 | pmid=14645853 | doi=10.1126/science.1088477 | pmc=1618876}}</ref> He has over 1000 original peer reviewed publications, and has edited over 30 books, including the Textbook of Interventional Cardiology (6th ed - Elsevier), and the Textbook of Cardiovascular Medicine (3rd ed - Lippincott Williams & Wilkins).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/governance/ |title=About Us &#124; Scripps Translational Science Institute |publisher=Stsiweb.org |accessdate=2010-05-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100412231647/http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/governance/ |archivedate=April 12, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nHis previous training was at the [[University of Rochester]] (medical school), [[University of California, San Francisco]] (internal medicine), and [[Johns Hopkins University]] (cardiology). Topol was a tenured Professor at the [[University of Michigan]] for 6 years. At age 36, Topol was named Chairman of Cardiovascular Medicine at the [[Cleveland Clinic]], where he is widely credited with leading its cardiovascular program to the topmost position in the US.<ref name=\"Cleveland Clinic\">{{cite journal|title=Cleveland Clinic Boasts the Nation's Top Heart Center for the 15th Straight Year |url=http://www.clevelandleader.com/print/10675 |journal=Cleveland Leader |year=2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100213041528/http://clevelandleader.com/print/10675 |archivedate=2010-02-13 }}</ref> In 2002 he founded the [[Cleveland Clinic Lerner College of Medicine]] and in 2003 he became a Professor of Genetics at [[Case Western Reserve University]] while maintaining his primary appointment at Cleveland Clinic.\n\nTopol departed from the Cleveland Clinic Lerner College of Medicine in 2006 following the removal of the Chief Academic Officer position, and continued on as a Professor of Genetics at [[Case Western Reserve University]]. He was then recruited by [[Scripps Health]] and [[The Scripps Research Institute]] in late 2006 to the post of Chief Academic Officer and Professor of Translational Genomics.<ref name=\"scripps.org\">http://www.scripps.org/news_items/2854-noted-cardiologist-eric-j-topol-comes-to-scripps</ref> In 2009, Topol worked with Gary and [[Mary West]] to create the [[West Wireless Health Institute]], made possible by their philanthropic gift, and leads the field in developing, validating and accelerating wireless medicine.\n\n==Genetics and genomics==\nAt the [[University of Virginia]], Topol authored his baccalaureate thesis in 1975 entitled \u201cProspects for Genetic Therapy in Man\u201d which concentrated on [[genetics]], and received a BA degree With Highest Distinction. During his training at [[Johns Hopkins University]], he was involved from the very first patient who was administered [[T-pa|t-PA]] in 1984, a genetically engineered protein.<ref name=\"rt-PA Collen & Topol et al\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Collen D, Topol EJ, Tiefenbrunn AJ, Gold HK, Weisfeldt ML, Sobel BE, Leinbach RC, Brinker JA, Ludbrook PA, Yasuda I | title= Coronary thrombolysis with recombinant human tissue-type plasminogen activator: a prospective, randomized, placebo-controlled trial | journal=Circulation |date=1 December 1984 | volume=70 | issue=6 | pages=1012\u20137 | pmid=6388898 | doi= 10.1161/01.CIR.70.6.1012 |doi-access=free |display-authors=3}}</ref> But it was not until 1996 that he started the first dedicated cardiovascular gene bank while at [[Cleveland Clinic]].<ref name=\"Thrombospondin Topol et al\">{{cite journal | doi= 10.1161/hc4701.100910 |doi-access=free |last1=Topol |first1=Eric J. |last2=McCarthy |first2=Jeanette |last3=Gabriel |first3=Stacey |last4=Moliterno |first4=David J. |last5=Rogers |first5=William J. |last6=Newby |first6=L. Kristin |last7=Freedman |first7=Matt |last8=Metivier |first8=Jennifer |last9=Cannata |first9=Ruth |last10=O\u2019Donnell |first10=Christopher J. |last11=Kottke-Marchant |first11=Kandice |last12=Murugesan |first12=Gurunathan |last13=Plow |first13=Edward F. |last14=Stenina |first14=Olga |last15=Daley |first15=George Q. |author16=GeneQuest Investigators and Collaborators |name-list-format=vanc | title= Single nucleotide polymorphisms in multiple novel thrombospondin genes may be associated with familial premature myocardial infarction | journal=Circulation |date=27 November 2001 |volume=104 |issue=22 |pages=2641\u20134 | pmid=11723011 |display-authors=3 }}</ref> This effort led to many discoveries in the genetics of cardiovascular disease, including the identification of key genes associated with heart attack. Both [[thrombospondin]] variants and the [[MEF2A]] deletion reports were recognized as top 10 advances by the American Heart Association in 2000 and 2004, as mentioned above. He was the Principal Investigator of the flagship National Institutes of Health Specialized Centers of Clinically Oriented Research (SCCOR) grant on the genomics of heart attack with a $17 million award in 2005.\nHis work in genetics has been recognized by the [[American College of Cardiology]] with the Simon Dack Award and Lecture in 2005 and by the [[European Society of Cardiology]] by the Andreas Gruentzig Award and Lecture in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org/images/uploads/EJTBibliography-May2010.doc |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726091821/http://www.stsiweb.org/images/uploads/EJTBibliography-May2010.doc |archive-date=2011-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nIn moving to Scripps in 2006, he started the Scripps Genomic Medicine program and recruited a large team to advance individualized medicine using genomic approaches.<ref name=\"scripps.org\"/> The group formed the Scripps Translational Science Institute,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101014194150/http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php |archive-date=2010-10-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which presently includes Drs. Steven Steinhubl,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org//about/bio/steinhubl |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-08-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810133109/http://www.stsiweb.org//about/bio/steinhubl |archive-date=2014-08-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Ali Torkamani,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/bio/torkamani |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928005654/http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/bio/torkamani |archive-date=2012-09-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Nathan Wineinger,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/bio/wineinger |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-10-31 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416010516/http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/bio/wineinger |archive-date=2013-04-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and has multiple NIH funded projects on genomics of cancer, aging, cardiovascular disease, pharmacogenomics and diabetes.  It is a major force in San Diego bringing together basic scientists and clinical investigators from [[Scripps Health]] and [[The Scripps Research Institute]] along with researchers from the [[Salk Institute]], [[Sanford-Burnham Medical Research Institute|Sanford-Burnham Institute]], the [[San Diego Supercomputer Center]], and the [[Children's Hospital of Philadelphia|Children's Hospital of Philadelphia]]. Each year since 2007 Scripps Genomic Medicine and the Scripps Translational Science Institute put together a major program entitled \"Future of Individualized Medicine\"<ref name=\"FOIM website\">[https://www.scripps.edu/science-and-medicine/translational-institute/about/events/foim/ Future of Individualized Medicine]</ref> (formerly \u201cFuture of Genomic Medicine\u201d) which attracts several hundred clinicians and scientists. In 2009, Topol led the team at Scripps to be the first center to perform routine genotyping of patients undergoing stenting for variants of the gene [[CYP2C19]], the major gene implicated in [[Plavix]] metabolism.<ref>{{cite news |last=Darc\u00e9 |first=Keith |date=30 October 2009 |title=Gene test guides care |website=Sign On San Diego |publisher=San Diego Union-Tribune, LLC |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2009/oct/30/heart-patients-who-show-mutation-are-unlikely-bene/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 November 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122083228/http://www3.signonsandiego.com/news/2009/oct/30/heart-patients-who-show-mutation-are-unlikely-bene/ }}</ref> The first large scale prospective study of consumer genomics, known as the [[Scripps Genomic Health Initiative]], was completed in 2010.  Also in 2010, he initiated the Association for Genomic Medicine that is dedicated to training physicians in genomics.<ref>{{cite web |first=Turna |last=Ray |date=12 May 2010 |title=Q&A: Eric Topol Discusses 'Genomic Medicine Academy' and Getting Docs Excited About Medicine Again |website=GenomeWeb |url=http://www.genomeweb.com/dxpgx/qa-eric-topol-discusses-genomic-medicine-academy-and-getting-docs-excited-about- |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-date=4 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304151642/http://www.genomeweb.com/dxpgx/qa-eric-topol-discusses-genomic-medicine-academy-and-getting-docs-excited-about- }}</ref>\n\n== Wireless medicine ==\nTopol has been involved with wireless medicine since its inception. He was the first physician to serve on CardioNet's Medical Advisory Board in 1999, the first dedicated wireless medicine company that performs real-time ECG remote, continuous rhythm monitoring. In 2007 he joined the Board of Sotera Wireless that has developed the first continuous non-invasive blood pressure monitoring device, which also captures all vital signs. In 2008 he forged a new educational program with [[Qualcomm]] and [[Scripps Health]] to train physicians in wireless medicine, a 2-year clinician scholar program: STSI Wireless Health Scholar. At the 2009 International Wireless [[CTIA - The Wireless Association|CTIA]] meeting, he gave the keynote address on wireless health, the first time this topic has ever been the subject of a CTIA plenary session: CTIA 2009 Keynote.  Also in 2009, he served as Co-Founder with Gary and Mary West to form the [[West Wireless Health Institute]]. He is the Vice-Chairman of the Institute and its Chief Innovation Officer. He presented at TEDMED the rapid progress being made in this field: TEDMED 2009 Lecture. In addition, in early 2010 Topol gave a wireless medicine presentation at the [[Consumer Electronic Show]]: CES 2010 Keynote Highlight. He led the first trial with the GE Vscan device GE Reports, a pocket high resolution, mobile ultrasound imaging device, introduced in the US in 2010 \"The Doctor Will \u201ce\u201d You Now\" and is currently leading clinical trials of heart rhythm and heart failure monitoring wireless devices.\n\n==NHS==\nHe was commissioned by [[Jeremy Hunt]] in 2018 to carry out a review of how the [[NHS]] workforce, will need to change \u201cto deliver a digital future\u201d.  His report suggested that within ten years most patients would be managing their own long-term conditions with wearable devices and sensors, and that that would be much more effective than occasional appointments with a doctor.  Patients would not be monitored in hospital but at home. This rise in regular monitoring would necessitate new workflows and frameworks in [[Digital Healthcare|digital healthcare]].<ref name=\"topol.hee.nhs.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://topol.hee.nhs.uk/|title=The Topol Review \u2014 NHS Health Education England|website=The Topol Review \u2014 NHS Health Education England|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> More nursing and physician associates would be required, enabling doctors to focus on the most difficult cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Could patients become their own doctors? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-47205496 |accessdate=14 February 2019 |publisher=BBC |date=12 February 2019}}</ref>  The report also recommended specific digital training for NHS staff and physicians.<ref name=\"topol.hee.nhs.uk\"/> His work on \"High-performance medicine\" that builds on this report was also published in ''Nature.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30617339-high-performance-medicine-the-convergence-of-human-and-artificial-intelligence/?dopt=Abstract|title=High-performance Medicine: The Convergence of Human and Artificial Intelligence|last=Ej|first=Topol|date=January 2019|website=Nature medicine|language=en|pmid=30617339|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Vioxx ==\nTopol served as chairman of cardiovascular medicine at [[Cleveland Clinic]] (1991-2005). Topol was one of the first researchers to question the cardiovascular safety of [[rofecoxib]] (Vioxx), culminating in the drug's ultimate withdrawal from the market. Topol's advocacy on the subject led to what ''The New York Times'' described as an \"unusually public dispute\" with the Cleveland Clinic's leadership over ties between the academic institution and the pharmaceutical industry,<ref name=\"nyt-ties\"/> ultimately leading to Topol's departure from the Clinic after his administrative position as head of the Clinic's academic program was abolished.\n\nTopol gained prominence as the first physician researcher to raise questions about the safety of [[rofecoxib]] (Vioxx).<ref name=\"Vioxx-2001-JAMA\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Mukherjee D, Nissen SE, Topol EJ | title=Risk of Cardiovascular Events Associated With Selective COX-2 Inhibitors | journal=JAMA | year=2001 | volume=286 | pages=954\u2013959 | pmid=11509060 | doi=10.1001/jama.286.8.954 | issue= 8| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7a377f62af8909f715570b30a16de2ffdb5210f3 }}</ref> Topol was highly critical of [[Merck & Co.|Merck]]'s handling of safety issues related to Vioxx. In a 2004 editorial in ''[[The New York Times]]'', he wrote that \"Merck finally had to acknowledge the truth [about the drug's cardiovascular risks], but only by accident.\"<ref name=\"nyt-oped\">{{cite news | work = [[The New York Times]] | first = Eric | last = Topol | date = October 2, 2004 | accessdate = July 9, 2010 | title = Good Riddance to a Bad Drug | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/02/opinion/02topol.html}}</ref> Topol also authored an editorial in the ''[[New England Journal of Medicine]]'', arguing that \"neither Merck nor the FDA fulfilled its responsibilities to the public\" and encouraging a \"full Congressional review\" of the situation.<ref name=\"nejm-oped\">{{cite journal |author=Topol EJ |title=Failing the public health&mdash;rofecoxib, Merck, and the FDA |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=351 |issue=17 |pages=1707\u20139 |date=October 2004 |pmid=15470193 |doi=10.1056/NEJMp048286 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5eef236867456f94365321fbd9f3eea9636496ea }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, [[Bethany McLean]], writing in ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'', questioned Topol's own potential financial conflicts of interest. She reported that Topol served as a scientific advisor to a [[hedge fund]] which profited substantially by [[short selling]] Merck stock, which plummeted due to the concerns about Vioxx which Topol had publicized.<ref name=\"fortune\">{{cite news | first = Bethany | last = McLean | authorlink = Bethany McLean | work = [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] | title = A Bitter Pill for One Merck Critic | url = http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2004/12/13/8214229/index.htm | date = December 13, 2004 | accessdate = July 16, 2010}}</ref> Topol denied giving the hedge fund advance information, and subsequently severed his ties to industry, donating all such income directly to charity.<ref name=\"nyt-ties\"/> In a 2005 ''[[Journal of the American Medical Association|JAMA]]'' commentary, Topol pointed to these allegations as an example of the complications that physicians can experience when associating with the investment industry, at the same time reiterating that \"no true conflict of interest existed in this case.\"<ref name=\"topol-investment\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Topol EJ, Blumenthal D |title=Physicians and the investment industry |journal=JAMA |volume=293 |issue=21 |pages=2654\u20137 |date=June 2005 |pmid=15928288 |doi=10.1001/jama.293.21.2654 |url=http://jama.ama-assn.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=15928288}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, Topol was subpoenaed in a [[class action lawsuit]] against Merck. He testified that Vioxx posed an \"extraordinary risk\", and that [[Raymond Gilmartin]], former [[chief executive officer]] of Merck, had contacted the head of the Cleveland Clinic board to complain about Topol's work on Vioxx.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news | publisher = Bloomberg | title = Merck's Vioxx Posed 'Extraordinary' Risk, Cardiologist Contends | first = Jef | last = Feeley |author2=Laurel Brubaker Calkins | date = December 3, 2005 | accessdate = July 24, 2010 | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=apd2ulXqRR9w}}</ref> Two days afterward, Topol was informed that the position as chief academic officer at the Cleveland Clinic had been abolished, and he was removed as [[provost (education)|provost]] of the Cleveland Clinic Lerner College of Medicine, which he had founded. The Clinic described the timing as coincidental.<ref name=\"specter\">{{cite book | first = Michael | last = Specter | authorlink = Michael Specter | title = Denialism: How Irrational Thinking Hinders Scientific Progress, Harms the Planet, and Threatens Our Lives | year = 2009 | publisher = [[Penguin Books]] | isbn = 978-1-59420-230-8 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/denialismhowirra00spec }}</ref>{{Page needed|date=March 2017}} ''The New York Times'' described Topol's demotion as part of an \"unusually public dispute\" between Topol and the Cleveland Clinic's chief executive, [[Delos Cosgrove]], and stated that Topol's criticism of Merck had focused scrutiny and criticism on the Clinic's deep and longstanding ties to the pharmaceutical and medical-device industries.<ref name=\"nyt-ties\">{{cite news | work = The New York Times | title = Ties to Industry Cloud a Clinic's Mission | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/17/business/17clinic.html | first = Reed | last = Abelson |first2=Stephanie |last2=Saul | date = December 17, 2005 | accessdate = July 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\nTopol was selected as one of the 12 \u201cRock Stars of Science\u201d by ''[[GQ]]'' and the [[Geoffrey Beene|Geoffrey Beene Foundation]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |date=2009 |publisher=Geoffrey Beene Foundation |url=http://www.geoffreybeene.com/rockstars/?page_id=1018 |title=Eric Topol |website=Geoffrey Beene Rock Stars of Science |accessdate=2010-05-12 |url-status=live |archive-date=2 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602051547/http://www.geoffreybeene.com/rockstars/?page_id=1018 }}</ref> He was elected to the [[American Society for Clinical Investigation]], the [[Association of American Physicians]], and the Johns Hopkins Society of Scholars. In 2004, he was elected to the [[Institute of Medicine]] of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]].<ref>{{cite press release |last1=Stencel |first1=Christine |last2=Shamir |first2=Judith |date=18 October 2004 |title=Institute of Medicine Elects 65 New Members, Five Foreign Associates |location=Washington |publisher=The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine |url=http://www8.nationalacademies.org/onpinews/newsitem.aspx?RecordID=10182004 |url-status=live |archive-date=31 October 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031035532/http://www8.nationalacademies.org/onpinews/newsitem.aspx?RecordID=10182004 }}</ref> He was named Doctor of the Decade by the [[Institute for Scientific Information]] for being one of the top 10 most cited medical researchers. In 2011, Topol received the Hutchinson Medal from the [[University of Rochester]] in addition to giving the commencement speech for the School of Medicine and Dentistry. In 2012, ''[[Modern Healthcare]]'' ranked Topol as the most influential physician executive in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Robbins |first=Gary |date=21 April 2012 |url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2012/apr/21/eric-topol-named-one-nations-50-best-doctors/ |title=San Diego's Topol named nation's top physician executive |newspaper=San Diego Union\u2013Tribune |accessdate=2012-04-23 |url-status=live |archive-date=19 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519131732/http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2012/apr/21/eric-topol-named-one-nations-50-best-doctors/ }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nEric Jeffrey Topol was born on 26 June 1954.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120053634/http://www.stsiweb.org:80/images/uploads/Eric_J_Topol_CV_October_2012.pdf|title=Curriculum Vitae Eric J. Topol, M.D|last=Eric|first=Topol|date=2012-10-01|website=stsiweb.org|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref> He is married to Susan Merriman Topol with whom he has two children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Topol, Eric. ''The Patient Will See You Now: The Future of Medicine Is in Your Hands''. New York: Basic Books, 2015 \u2014 {{ISBN|9780465054749}} <ref>{{cite news | author=Chitty, Mary | title=The Future According to Topol | date=January 14, 2015 | work=Clinical Informatics News | publisher=Cambridge Healthtech Institute | location=Needham, Massachusetts, United States | url=http://www.clinicalinformaticsnews.com/2015/1/14/future-according-to-topol.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Review of \"The Patient Will See You Now\" by Eric Topol|author=Jauhar, Sandeep|date=13 February 2015|newspaper=The New York Times||url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/15/books/review/the-patient-will-see-you-now-by-eric-topol.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|author=Klass, Perri|authorlink=Perri Klass|title=Review of \"The Patient Will See You Now\" by Eric Topol|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=16 January 2015|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/book-review-the-patient-will-see-you-now-on-future-of-medicine-by-eric-topol/2015/01/16/4b345b00-9761-11e4-aabd-d0b93ff613d5_story.html}}</ref>\n* Topol, Eric. ''The Creative Destruction of Medicine: How the Digital Revolution Will Create Better Health Care''. New York: Basic Books, 2012 \u2014 {{ISBN|9780465025503}}<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Healthcare Informatics Research|date=September 2013|volume=19|issue=3|pages=229\u2013231|doi=10.4258/hir.2013.19.3.229|pmc=3810531|title=Book Review: \"Creative Destruction of Medicine: How the Digital Revolution Will Create Better Health Care\" by Eric Topol|author=Kim, Jung A. }}</ref>\n* Topol, Eric J., and Paul S. Teirstein. 1st edition, 1989; ''Textbook of Interventional Cardiology'', 7th edition. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2015 \u2014 {{ISBN|9780323340380}}; 8th edition, 2019 \u2014 {{ISBN|9780323568142}}\n* Topol, Eric J. ''Deep Medicine'', 2019 \u2014 {{ISBN|9781541644649}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Review of ''Deep Medicine'' by Eric Topol|website=Kirkus Reviews|year=2019|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/eric-topol/deep-medicine/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Atkinson, Robert D.|authorlink=Robert D. Atkinson|title=Review of ''Deep Medicine'' by Eric Topol|website=New York Journal of Books|year=2019|url=https://www.nyjournalofbooks.com/book-review/deep-medicine}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Full Genome Sequencing]]\n* [[Exome Sequencing]]\n* [[Personal genomics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stsiweb.org/about/leadership/founder/ Topol's profile at Scripps Translational Science Institute]\n*[http://www.scripps.org/physicians/5497-topol/ Topol's profile at Scripps Health]\n*[http://www.ted.com/talks/eric_topol_the_wireless_future_of_medicine.html Topol's talk at TEDMED 2009 conference]\n* {{cite web |last=Roberts |first=Russ |title=Topol on ''The Creative Destruction of Medicine'' |url=http://www.econtalk.org/archives/_featuring/eric_topol/ |work=[[EconTalk]] |publisher=[[Library of Economics and Liberty]] |authorlink=Russ Roberts |date=April 1, 2013}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/video/rock-center/50582822#50582822 |title=iDoctor: Could a smartphone be the future of medicine? |publisher=NBC News |date=January 24, 2013}} Video (08:51) Topol's interview by Nancy Snyderman for the television program ''Rock Center''.<!--also posted at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r13uYs7jglg-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Topol, Eric}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Scripps Research Institute faculty]]\n[[Category:American cardiologists]]\n[[Category:American geneticists]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan faculty]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Clinic people]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox scientist/Wikidata\n|fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n\n'''Eric Jeffrey Topol''' (born 1954) is an American [[cardiology|cardiologist]], [[geneticist]], author, and scientist. \nHe is the Founder and Director of the Scripps Research Translational Institute<ref name=\"STSI website\">[http://www.stsiweb.org Scripps Translational Science Institute]</ref> in La Jolla, California. He also serves as the Chief Academic Officer for Scripps Health, a Professor of Genomics at [[The Scripps Research Institute]], and a Senior Consultant at the Division of Cardiovascular Diseases at Scripps Clinic. He is editor-in-chief of [[Medscape]] and ''theheart.org''. He has published 3 bestseller books on the future of medicine. His most recent book ''Deep Medicine: How Artificial Intelligence Can Make Healthcare Human Again'' came out in 2019, which focuses on how AI empowers physicians and revolutionizes the health care industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hachettebookgroup.com/titles/eric-topol/deep-medicine/9781541644632/|title=Deep Medicine|publisher=Hachette Book Group|accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref>''The Creative Destruction of Medicine'' which examined the impact of both the genomic and wireless revolutions on the health care system.  His book ''The Patient Will See You Now'', published in 2015, explores how smartphones, big data, and technology are combining to democratize health care. In 2016, Topol co-founded<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-smart-medicine-solution-to-the-health-care-crisis-1499443449|title=The Smart-Medicine Solution to the Health-Care Crisis|last=Topol|first=Eric|date=2017-07-07|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2017-07-08|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> a company developing an individual-centric health data platform. \n\nIn 2016, Topol was awarded a $207M grant from the [[National Institutes of Health]] to lead a significant part of the [[Precision Medicine Initiative]], a one million American prospective research program.<ref>{{cite web |last=Comstock |first=Jonah |date=6 October 2016 |title=NIH expands grant for Scripps-led Precision Medicine group to $207M |website=MobiHealthNews |publisher=HIMSS Media |url=http://www.mobihealthnews.com/content/nih-expands-grant-scripps-led-precision-medicine-group-207m }}</ref>\n\n== Research and training ==\nTopol's research career has been in two major areas: clinical development of new drugs and devices and genomics. Topol pioneered the development of many medications that are routinely used in medical practice including [[T-pa|t-PA]], [[Plavix]], [[Angiomax]], and [[Reopro|ReoPro]]. He has led worldwide clinical trials in over 40 countries involving over 200,000 patients (First in series \u2013 GUSTO trials).<ref name=\"GUSTO-1993-1\">{{cite journal | author=The GUSTO investigators | title=An international randomized trial comparing four thrombolytic strategies for acute myocardial infarction. The GUSTO investigators | journal=New England Journal of Medicine | year=1993 | volume=329 | issue=10 | pages=673\u201382 | pmid=8204123 | doi=10.1056/NEJM199309023291001| hdl=1765/5468 | url=http://repub.eur.nl/pub/5468 }}</ref> His work in the genomics of heart attack has led to discovery of key genes ([[Myocyte-specific enhancer factor 2A|MEF2A]] deletion, [[Thrombospondin]] variants) which led to recognition by the American Heart Association top 10 research advances in 2001 and 2003.<ref name=\"Thrombospondin Topol et al\"/><ref name=\"MEF2A-2003-Science\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wang L, Fan C, Topol SE, Topol EJ, Wang Q | title=Mutation of MEF2A in an Inherited Disorder with Features of Coronary Artery Disease | journal=Science | year=2003 | volume=302 | issue=5650 | pages=1578\u201381 | pmid=14645853 | doi=10.1126/science.1088477 | pmc=1618876}}</ref> He has over 1000 original peer reviewed publications, and has edited over 30 books, including the Textbook of Interventional Cardiology (6th ed - Elsevier), and the Textbook of Cardiovascular Medicine (3rd ed - Lippincott Williams & Wilkins).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/governance/ |title=About Us &#124; Scripps Translational Science Institute |publisher=Stsiweb.org |accessdate=2010-05-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100412231647/http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/governance/ |archivedate=April 12, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nHis previous training was at the [[University of Rochester]] (medical school), [[University of California, San Francisco]] (internal medicine), and [[Johns Hopkins University]] (cardiology). Topol was a tenured Professor at the [[University of Michigan]] for 6 years. At age 36, Topol was named Chairman of Cardiovascular Medicine at the [[Cleveland Clinic]], where he is widely credited with leading its cardiovascular program to the topmost position in the US.<ref name=\"Cleveland Clinic\">{{cite journal|title=Cleveland Clinic Boasts the Nation's Top Heart Center for the 15th Straight Year |url=http://www.clevelandleader.com/print/10675 |journal=Cleveland Leader |year=2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100213041528/http://clevelandleader.com/print/10675 |archivedate=2010-02-13 }}</ref> In 2002 he founded the [[Cleveland Clinic Lerner College of Medicine]] and in 2003 he became a Professor of Genetics at [[Case Western Reserve University]] while maintaining his primary appointment at Cleveland Clinic.\n\nTopol departed from the Cleveland Clinic Lerner College of Medicine in 2006 following the removal of the Chief Academic Officer position, and continued on as a Professor of Genetics at [[Case Western Reserve University]]. He was then recruited by [[Scripps Health]] and [[The Scripps Research Institute]] in late 2006 to the post of Chief Academic Officer and Professor of Translational Genomics.<ref name=\"scripps.org\">http://www.scripps.org/news_items/2854-noted-cardiologist-eric-j-topol-comes-to-scripps</ref> In 2009, Topol worked with Gary and [[Mary West]] to create the [[West Wireless Health Institute]], made possible by their philanthropic gift, and leads the field in developing, validating and accelerating wireless medicine.\n\n==Genetics and genomics==\nAt the [[University of Virginia]], Topol authored his baccalaureate thesis in 1975 entitled \u201cProspects for Genetic Therapy in Man\u201d which concentrated on [[genetics]], and received a BA degree With Highest Distinction. During his training at [[Johns Hopkins University]], he was involved from the very first patient who was administered [[T-pa|t-PA]] in 1984, a genetically engineered protein.<ref name=\"rt-PA Collen & Topol et al\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Collen D, Topol EJ, Tiefenbrunn AJ, Gold HK, Weisfeldt ML, Sobel BE, Leinbach RC, Brinker JA, Ludbrook PA, Yasuda I | title= Coronary thrombolysis with recombinant human tissue-type plasminogen activator: a prospective, randomized, placebo-controlled trial | journal=Circulation |date=1 December 1984 | volume=70 | issue=6 | pages=1012\u20137 | pmid=6388898 | doi= 10.1161/01.CIR.70.6.1012 |doi-access=free |display-authors=3}}</ref> But it was not until 1996 that he started the first dedicated cardiovascular gene bank while at [[Cleveland Clinic]].<ref name=\"Thrombospondin Topol et al\">{{cite journal | doi= 10.1161/hc4701.100910 |doi-access=free |last1=Topol |first1=Eric J. |last2=McCarthy |first2=Jeanette |last3=Gabriel |first3=Stacey |last4=Moliterno |first4=David J. |last5=Rogers |first5=William J. |last6=Newby |first6=L. Kristin |last7=Freedman |first7=Matt |last8=Metivier |first8=Jennifer |last9=Cannata |first9=Ruth |last10=O\u2019Donnell |first10=Christopher J. |last11=Kottke-Marchant |first11=Kandice |last12=Murugesan |first12=Gurunathan |last13=Plow |first13=Edward F. |last14=Stenina |first14=Olga |last15=Daley |first15=George Q. |author16=GeneQuest Investigators and Collaborators |name-list-format=vanc | title= Single nucleotide polymorphisms in multiple novel thrombospondin genes may be associated with familial premature myocardial infarction | journal=Circulation |date=27 November 2001 |volume=104 |issue=22 |pages=2641\u20134 | pmid=11723011 |display-authors=3 }}</ref> This effort led to many discoveries in the genetics of cardiovascular disease, including the identification of key genes associated with heart attack. Both [[thrombospondin]] variants and the [[MEF2A]] deletion reports were recognized as top 10 advances by the American Heart Association in 2000 and 2004, as mentioned above. He was the Principal Investigator of the flagship National Institutes of Health Specialized Centers of Clinically Oriented Research (SCCOR) grant on the genomics of heart attack with a $17 million award in 2005.\nHis work in genetics has been recognized by the [[American College of Cardiology]] with the Simon Dack Award and Lecture in 2005 and by the [[European Society of Cardiology]] by the Andreas Gruentzig Award and Lecture in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org/images/uploads/EJTBibliography-May2010.doc |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726091821/http://www.stsiweb.org/images/uploads/EJTBibliography-May2010.doc |archive-date=2011-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nIn moving to Scripps in 2006, he started the Scripps Genomic Medicine program and recruited a large team to advance individualized medicine using genomic approaches.<ref name=\"scripps.org\"/> The group formed the Scripps Translational Science Institute,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101014194150/http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php |archive-date=2010-10-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which presently includes Drs. Steven Steinhubl,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org//about/bio/steinhubl |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-08-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810133109/http://www.stsiweb.org//about/bio/steinhubl |archive-date=2014-08-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Ali Torkamani,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/bio/torkamani |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928005654/http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/bio/torkamani |archive-date=2012-09-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Nathan Wineinger,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/bio/wineinger |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-10-31 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416010516/http://www.stsiweb.org/index.php/about/bio/wineinger |archive-date=2013-04-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and has multiple NIH funded projects on genomics of cancer, aging, cardiovascular disease, pharmacogenomics and diabetes.  It is a major force in San Diego bringing together basic scientists and clinical investigators from [[Scripps Health]] and [[The Scripps Research Institute]] along with researchers from the [[Salk Institute]], [[Sanford-Burnham Medical Research Institute|Sanford-Burnham Institute]], the [[San Diego Supercomputer Center]], and the [[Children's Hospital of Philadelphia|Children\u2019s Hospital of Philadelphia]]. Each year since 2007 Scripps Genomic Medicine and the Scripps Translational Science Institute put together a major program entitled \"Future of Individualized Medicine\"<ref name=\"FOIM website\">[https://www.scripps.edu/science-and-medicine/translational-institute/about/events/foim/ Future of Individualized Medicine]</ref> (formerly \u201cFuture of Genomic Medicine\u201d) which attracts several hundred clinicians and scientists. In 2009, Topol led the team at Scripps to be the first center to perform routine genotyping of patients undergoing stenting for variants of the gene [[CYP2C19]], the major gene implicated in [[Plavix]] metabolism.<ref>{{cite news |last=Darc\u00e9 |first=Keith |date=30 October 2009 |title=Gene test guides care |website=Sign On San Diego |publisher=San Diego Union-Tribune, LLC |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2009/oct/30/heart-patients-who-show-mutation-are-unlikely-bene/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 November 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122083228/http://www3.signonsandiego.com/news/2009/oct/30/heart-patients-who-show-mutation-are-unlikely-bene/ }}</ref> The first large scale prospective study of consumer genomics, known as the [[Scripps Genomic Health Initiative]], was completed in 2010.  Also in 2010, he initiated the Association for Genomic Medicine that is dedicated to training physicians in genomics.<ref>{{cite web |first=Turna |last=Ray |date=12 May 2010 |title=Q&A: Eric Topol Discusses 'Genomic Medicine Academy' and Getting Docs Excited About Medicine Again |website=GenomeWeb |url=http://www.genomeweb.com/dxpgx/qa-eric-topol-discusses-genomic-medicine-academy-and-getting-docs-excited-about- |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-date=4 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304151642/http://www.genomeweb.com/dxpgx/qa-eric-topol-discusses-genomic-medicine-academy-and-getting-docs-excited-about- }}</ref>\n\n== Wireless medicine ==\nTopol has been involved with wireless medicine since its inception. He was the first physician to serve on CardioNet's Medical Advisory Board in 1999, the first dedicated wireless medicine company that performs real-time ECG remote, continuous rhythm monitoring. In 2007 he joined the Board of Sotera Wireless that has developed the first continuous non-invasive blood pressure monitoring device, which also captures all vital signs. In 2008 he forged a new educational program with [[Qualcomm]] and [[Scripps Health]] to train physicians in wireless medicine, a 2-year clinician scholar program: STSI Wireless Health Scholar. At the 2009 International Wireless [[CTIA - The Wireless Association|CTIA]] meeting, he gave the keynote address on wireless health, the first time this topic has ever been the subject of a CTIA plenary session: CTIA 2009 Keynote.  Also in 2009, he served as Co-Founder with Gary and Mary West to form the [[West Wireless Health Institute]]. He is the Vice-Chairman of the Institute and its Chief Innovation Officer. He presented at TEDMED the rapid progress being made in this field: TEDMED 2009 Lecture. In addition, in early 2010 Topol gave a wireless medicine presentation at the [[Consumer Electronic Show]]: CES 2010 Keynote Highlight. He led the first trial with the GE Vscan device GE Reports, a pocket high resolution, mobile ultrasound imaging device, introduced in the US in 2010 \"The Doctor Will \u201ce\u201d You Now\" and is currently leading clinical trials of heart rhythm and heart failure monitoring wireless devices.\n\n==NHS==\nHe was commissioned by [[Jeremy Hunt]] in 2018 to carry out a review of how the [[NHS]] workforce, will need to change \u201cto deliver a digital future\u201d.  His report suggested that within ten years most patients would be managing their own long-term conditions with wearable devices and sensors, and that that would be much more effective than occasional appointments with a doctor.  Patients would not be monitored in hospital but at home. This rise in regular monitoring would necessitate new workflows and frameworks in [[Digital Healthcare|digital healthcare]].<ref name=\"topol.hee.nhs.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://topol.hee.nhs.uk/|title=The Topol Review \u2014 NHS Health Education England|website=The Topol Review \u2014 NHS Health Education England|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> More nursing and physician associates would be required, enabling doctors to focus on the most difficult cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Could patients become their own doctors? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-47205496 |accessdate=14 February 2019 |publisher=BBC |date=12 February 2019}}</ref>  The report also recommended specific digital training for NHS staff and physicians.<ref name=\"topol.hee.nhs.uk\"/> His work on \"High-performance medicine\" that builds on this report was also published in ''Nature.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30617339-high-performance-medicine-the-convergence-of-human-and-artificial-intelligence/?dopt=Abstract|title=High-performance Medicine: The Convergence of Human and Artificial Intelligence|last=Ej|first=Topol|date=January 2019|website=Nature medicine|language=en|pmid=30617339|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Vioxx ==\nTopol served as chairman of cardiovascular medicine at [[Cleveland Clinic]] (1991-2005). Topol was one of the first researchers to question the cardiovascular safety of [[rofecoxib]] (Vioxx), culminating in the drug's ultimate withdrawal from the market. Topol's advocacy on the subject led to what ''The New York Times'' described as an \"unusually public dispute\" with the Cleveland Clinic's leadership over ties between the academic institution and the pharmaceutical industry,<ref name=\"nyt-ties\"/> ultimately leading to Topol's departure from the Clinic after his administrative position as head of the Clinic's academic program was abolished.\n\nTopol gained prominence as the first physician researcher to raise questions about the safety of [[rofecoxib]] (Vioxx).<ref name=\"Vioxx-2001-JAMA\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Mukherjee D, Nissen SE, Topol EJ | title=Risk of Cardiovascular Events Associated With Selective COX-2 Inhibitors | journal=JAMA | year=2001 | volume=286 | pages=954\u2013959 | pmid=11509060 | doi=10.1001/jama.286.8.954 | issue= 8| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7a377f62af8909f715570b30a16de2ffdb5210f3 }}</ref> Topol was highly critical of [[Merck & Co.|Merck]]'s handling of safety issues related to Vioxx. In a 2004 editorial in ''[[The New York Times]]'', he wrote that \"Merck finally had to acknowledge the truth [about the drug's cardiovascular risks], but only by accident.\"<ref name=\"nyt-oped\">{{cite news | work = [[The New York Times]] | first = Eric | last = Topol | date = October 2, 2004 | accessdate = July 9, 2010 | title = Good Riddance to a Bad Drug | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/02/opinion/02topol.html}}</ref> Topol also authored an editorial in the ''[[New England Journal of Medicine]]'', arguing that \"neither Merck nor the FDA fulfilled its responsibilities to the public\" and encouraging a \"full Congressional review\" of the situation.<ref name=\"nejm-oped\">{{cite journal |author=Topol EJ |title=Failing the public health&mdash;rofecoxib, Merck, and the FDA |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=351 |issue=17 |pages=1707\u20139 |date=October 2004 |pmid=15470193 |doi=10.1056/NEJMp048286 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5eef236867456f94365321fbd9f3eea9636496ea }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, [[Bethany McLean]], writing in ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'', questioned Topol's own potential financial conflicts of interest. She reported that Topol served as a scientific advisor to a [[hedge fund]] which profited substantially by [[short selling]] Merck stock, which plummeted due to the concerns about Vioxx which Topol had publicized.<ref name=\"fortune\">{{cite news | first = Bethany | last = McLean | authorlink = Bethany McLean | work = [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] | title = A Bitter Pill for One Merck Critic | url = http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2004/12/13/8214229/index.htm | date = December 13, 2004 | accessdate = July 16, 2010}}</ref> Topol denied giving the hedge fund advance information, and subsequently severed his ties to industry, donating all such income directly to charity.<ref name=\"nyt-ties\"/> In a 2005 ''[[Journal of the American Medical Association|JAMA]]'' commentary, Topol pointed to these allegations as an example of the complications that physicians can experience when associating with the investment industry, at the same time reiterating that \"no true conflict of interest existed in this case.\"<ref name=\"topol-investment\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Topol EJ, Blumenthal D |title=Physicians and the investment industry |journal=JAMA |volume=293 |issue=21 |pages=2654\u20137 |date=June 2005 |pmid=15928288 |doi=10.1001/jama.293.21.2654 |url=http://jama.ama-assn.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=15928288}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, Topol was subpoenaed in a [[class action lawsuit]] against Merck. He testified that Vioxx posed an \"extraordinary risk\", and that [[Raymond Gilmartin]], former [[chief executive officer]] of Merck, had contacted the head of the Cleveland Clinic board to complain about Topol's work on Vioxx.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news | publisher = Bloomberg | title = Merck's Vioxx Posed 'Extraordinary' Risk, Cardiologist Contends | first = Jef | last = Feeley |author2=Laurel Brubaker Calkins | date = December 3, 2005 | accessdate = July 24, 2010 | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=apd2ulXqRR9w}}</ref> Two days afterward, Topol was informed that the position as chief academic officer at the Cleveland Clinic had been abolished, and he was removed as [[provost (education)|provost]] of the Cleveland Clinic Lerner College of Medicine, which he had founded. The Clinic described the timing as coincidental.<ref name=\"specter\">{{cite book | first = Michael | last = Specter | authorlink = Michael Specter | title = Denialism: How Irrational Thinking Hinders Scientific Progress, Harms the Planet, and Threatens Our Lives | year = 2009 | publisher = [[Penguin Books]] | isbn = 978-1-59420-230-8 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/denialismhowirra00spec }}</ref>{{Page needed|date=March 2017}} ''The New York Times'' described Topol's demotion as part of an \"unusually public dispute\" between Topol and the Cleveland Clinic's chief executive, [[Delos Cosgrove]], and stated that Topol's criticism of Merck had focused scrutiny and criticism on the Clinic's deep and longstanding ties to the pharmaceutical and medical-device industries.<ref name=\"nyt-ties\">{{cite news | work = The New York Times | title = Ties to Industry Cloud a Clinic's Mission | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/17/business/17clinic.html | first = Reed | last = Abelson |first2=Stephanie |last2=Saul | date = December 17, 2005 | accessdate = July 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\nTopol was selected as one of the 12 \u201cRock Stars of Science\u201d by ''[[GQ]]'' and the [[Geoffrey Beene|Geoffrey Beene Foundation]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |date=2009 |publisher=Geoffrey Beene Foundation |url=http://www.geoffreybeene.com/rockstars/?page_id=1018 |title=Eric Topol |website=Geoffrey Beene Rock Stars of Science |accessdate=2010-05-12 |url-status=live |archive-date=2 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602051547/http://www.geoffreybeene.com/rockstars/?page_id=1018 }}</ref> He was elected to the [[American Society for Clinical Investigation]], the [[Association of American Physicians]], and the Johns Hopkins Society of Scholars. In 2004, he was elected to the [[Institute of Medicine]] of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]].<ref>{{cite press release |last1=Stencel |first1=Christine |last2=Shamir |first2=Judith |date=18 October 2004 |title=Institute of Medicine Elects 65 New Members, Five Foreign Associates |location=Washington |publisher=The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine |url=http://www8.nationalacademies.org/onpinews/newsitem.aspx?RecordID=10182004 |url-status=live |archive-date=31 October 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031035532/http://www8.nationalacademies.org/onpinews/newsitem.aspx?RecordID=10182004 }}</ref> He was named Doctor of the Decade by the [[Institute for Scientific Information]] for being one of the top 10 most cited medical researchers. In 2011, Topol received the Hutchinson Medal from the [[University of Rochester]] in addition to giving the commencement speech for the School of Medicine and Dentistry. In 2012, ''[[Modern Healthcare]]'' ranked Topol as the most influential physician executive in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Robbins |first=Gary |date=21 April 2012 |url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2012/apr/21/eric-topol-named-one-nations-50-best-doctors/ |title=San Diego's Topol named nation's top physician executive |newspaper=San Diego Union\u2013Tribune |accessdate=2012-04-23 |url-status=live |archive-date=19 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519131732/http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2012/apr/21/eric-topol-named-one-nations-50-best-doctors/ }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nEric Jeffrey Topol was born on 26 June 1954.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120053634/http://www.stsiweb.org:80/images/uploads/Eric_J_Topol_CV_October_2012.pdf|title=Curriculum Vitae Eric J. Topol, M.D|last=Eric|first=Topol|date=2012-10-01|website=stsiweb.org|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref> He is married to Susan Merriman Topol with whom he has two children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Topol, Eric. ''The Patient Will See You Now: The Future of Medicine Is in Your Hands''. New York: Basic Books, 2015 \u2014 {{ISBN|9780465054749}} <ref>{{cite news | author=Chitty, Mary | title=The Future According to Topol | date=January 14, 2015 | work=Clinical Informatics News | publisher=Cambridge Healthtech Institute | location=Needham, Massachusetts, United States | url=http://www.clinicalinformaticsnews.com/2015/1/14/future-according-to-topol.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Review of \"The Patient Will See You Now\" by Eric Topol|author=Jauhar, Sandeep|date=13 February 2015|newspaper=The New York Times||url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/15/books/review/the-patient-will-see-you-now-by-eric-topol.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|author=Klass, Perri|authorlink=Perri Klass|title=Review of \"The Patient Will See You Now\" by Eric Topol|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=16 January 2015|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/book-review-the-patient-will-see-you-now-on-future-of-medicine-by-eric-topol/2015/01/16/4b345b00-9761-11e4-aabd-d0b93ff613d5_story.html}}</ref>\n* Topol, Eric. ''The Creative Destruction of Medicine: How the Digital Revolution Will Create Better Health Care''. New York: Basic Books, 2012 \u2014 {{ISBN|9780465025503}}<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Healthcare Informatics Research|date=September 2013|volume=19|issue=3|pages=229\u2013231|doi=10.4258/hir.2013.19.3.229|pmc=3810531|title=Book Review: \"Creative Destruction of Medicine: How the Digital Revolution Will Create Better Health Care\" by Eric Topol|author=Kim, Jung A. }}</ref>\n* Topol, Eric J., and Paul S. Teirstein. 1st edition, 1989; ''Textbook of Interventional Cardiology'', 7th edition. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2015 \u2014 {{ISBN|9780323340380}}; 8th edition, 2019 \u2014 {{ISBN|9780323568142}}\n* Topol, Eric J. ''Deep Medicine'', 2019 \u2014 {{ISBN|9781541644649}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Review of ''Deep Medicine'' by Eric Topol|website=Kirkus Reviews|year=2019|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/eric-topol/deep-medicine/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Atkinson, Robert D.|authorlink=Robert D. Atkinson|title=Review of ''Deep Medicine'' by Eric Topol|website=New York Journal of Books|year=2019|url=https://www.nyjournalofbooks.com/book-review/deep-medicine}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Full Genome Sequencing]]\n* [[Exome Sequencing]]\n* [[Personal genomics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stsiweb.org/about/leadership/founder/ Topol's profile at Scripps Translational Science Institute]\n*[http://www.scripps.org/physicians/5497-topol/ Topol's profile at Scripps Health]\n*[http://www.ted.com/talks/eric_topol_the_wireless_future_of_medicine.html Topol's talk at TEDMED 2009 conference]\n* {{cite web |last=Roberts |first=Russ |title=Topol on ''The Creative Destruction of Medicine'' |url=http://www.econtalk.org/archives/_featuring/eric_topol/ |work=[[EconTalk]] |publisher=[[Library of Economics and Liberty]] |authorlink=Russ Roberts |date=April 1, 2013}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/video/rock-center/50582822#50582822 |title=iDoctor: Could a smartphone be the future of medicine? |publisher=NBC News |date=January 24, 2013}} Video (08:51) Topol's interview by Nancy Snyderman for the television program ''Rock Center''.<!--also posted at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r13uYs7jglg-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Topol, Eric}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Scripps Research Institute faculty]]\n[[Category:American cardiologists]]\n[[Category:American geneticists]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan faculty]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Clinic people]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGenetics and genomics:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Topol"}
{"title_page": "David Alton", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Alton of Liverpool\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of Saint Gregory the Great|KCSG]] [[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George|KCMCO]]\n| image= Official portrait of Lord Alton of Liverpool crop 2, 2019.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| office1 = [[Member of the House of Lords]] <br>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start1 = 17 June 1997<br />[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| term_end1 =\n| office = [[Liberal Chief Whip]]\n| term_start = 1985\n| term_end = 11 June 1987\n| leader = [[David Steel]]\n| preceded = [[Alan Beith]]\n| succeeded = [[Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness|Jim Wallace]]\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Liverpool Mossley Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Mossley Hill]]<br /><small>[[Liverpool Edge Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Edge Hill]] (1979\u20131983)</small>\n| term_start3 = 30 March 1979\n| term_end3 = 1 May 1997\n| predecessor3 = [[Arthur Irvine|Sir Arthur Irvine]]\n| successor3 = ''Constituency abolished''\n| birthname = David Patrick Paul Alton\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|3|15}}\n| birth_place = London\n| party = None ([[Crossbencher|Crossbench]])\n| otherparty = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] (1972\u20131988)<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] (1988\u20131997)\n| alma_mater = [[Liverpool Hope University]]\n| spouse = Elizabeth Bell\n| children = 4\n}}\n'''David Patrick Paul Alton, Baron Alton of Liverpool''', [[Order of Saint Gregory the Great|KCSG]], [[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George|KCMCO]] (born 15 March 1951) is a British politician.\n\nHe is a former [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] and later [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] Member of Parliament who has sat as a [[Crossbencher|crossbench]] member of the [[House of Lords]] since 1997 when he was made a [[life peer]]. A [[Catholic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/why-michael-heseltine-is-like-a-hamster-1621398.html|title=Why Michael Heseltine is like a hamster|work=The Independent|date=28 May 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aJ3CQTnZHoVc&refer=uk|title=First Human-Animal Embryos in U.K. Bring Opposition (Update1)|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/29/weekinreview/ideas-trends-just-what-politicians-needed-a-patron-saint.html?pagewanted=2&src=pm The New York Times]</ref> he has advanced [[anti-abortion]] causes. Alton is also known for his human rights work including the co-founding of Jubilee Action, the children's charity (which changed its name to Chance for Childhood in 2014), and serves as chair, patron or trustee of several charities and voluntary organisations.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.jesuit.org.uk/creative-bridge-between-past-and-present |title = Creative bridge between the past and present &#124; Jesuits in Britain}}</ref>\n\n==Education and entry into politics==\nBorn in London on 15 March 1951,<ref name=\"THE\">{{cite web|title=In the news: David Alton|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=156736|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|date=26 January 2001|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Alton of Liverpool|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/26959.stm|work=Democracy Live|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> His father was a [[7th Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|Desert Rat]] who had served in the [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]], and then worked for the Ford Motor Company. His mother was a native Irish speaker from the West of Ireland. After being rehoused from the East End, Alton was brought up in a council flat on an overspill council estate. He passed a scholarship exam to join the first intake of a new Jesuit grammar school and was educated at the [[Campion School, Hornchurch]], Essex, and [[Liverpool Hope University|Christ's College of Education, Liverpool]].<ref name=\"THE\" /><ref name=\"davidalton.about\">{{Cite web | url=https://davidalton.net/about/ |title = About|date = 12 December 2010}}</ref> He began his career as a teacher and, in 1972, he was elected as a Liberal to [[Liverpool City Council]] as Britain's youngest city councillor. Alton was elected for the Low Hill ward, serving from 1972 to 1974, then, after the Local Government Act 1974, he was elected for the Smithdown ward where he served for the next six years. Ashton was also a member of [[Merseyside County Council]] for the Smithdown division from 1974 to 1977 and chairman of the housing committee. He was deputy leader of Liverpool City Council from 1975 to 1978.<ref name=\"davidalton.about\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nAlton was elected as Member of Parliament for [[Liverpool Edge Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Edge Hill]] at a [[1979 Liverpool Edge Hill by-election|by-election in 1979]] for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], when he became the \"[[Baby of the House]]\". achieving a record swing of 36.8% and 64% of the vote. He won the seat the day after the Callaghan Government was defeated in a vote of confidence and the 1979 General Election being called. He became the shortest lived MP, a member for less than a week, and made his Maiden Speech within three hours of taking his seat. Five weeks later he was re-elected and went on to serve as a Liverpool MP for 18 years, before standing down. He was the only new member of a Parliamentary Party of 11 MPs.  He campaigned on the slogan \u201cEveryone Knows Someone Who Has Been Helped by David Alton.\u201d<ref name=\"davidalton.about\"/> He was notably a very short-serving Baby of the House, as [[Stephen Dorrell]], who was a year younger than Alton, was elected at the 1979 election.\n\n[[File:DA - Everone knows someone.jpg|thumb|left|David Alton and his 1979 by-election campaign poster]]\n\nWhen the Edge Hill constituency was abolished for the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]], he was elected to represent the new [[Liverpool Mossley Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Mossley Hill]] constituency.\n\nFrom 1979 to 1988 he served at various times as spokesman on the environment, home affairs, Northern Ireland and as [[Chief Whip]]. He is known for his strongly [[anti-abortion]] position, and in 1987 he resigned as Chief Whip to campaign for his unsuccessful [[private member's bill]] which aimed to stop late abortions. He became a [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] MP when the Liberal Party merged with the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]] in 1988, but he had difficult relations with parts of the party, especially over attempts to make the party adopt a position [[Abortion-rights movements|in favor of abortion rights]]. In 1992, he announced that he would not stand again as a Liberal Democrat after the party passed a policy that he believed committed the party to support abortion for the first time.  A motion passed in Spring 1993 stating that the party had no position on the substantive issue of abortion spared him delivering on the promise.\n\nHe stood down as an MP at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. He was made a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Alton of Liverpool''', of [[Mossley Hill]] in the County of Merseyside<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54743 |date=18 April 1997 |page=4707 |supp=y }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54809 |date=17 June 1997 |page=7011 }}</ref> as a personal choice of [[John Major]] in the [[Dissolution Honours]], and took his seat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[crossbencher]].\n\nLord Alton is chairman of the British-DPRK All-Party Parliamentary Group, and visited Pyongyang in October 2010<ref>http://175.45.179.68/English/Political/HomeNews%5Cnews10263.htm {{dead link|date=September 2013}}</ref> when he had talks with leaders of the North Korean government including Choe Thae Bok, chairman of the [[Supreme People's Assembly]],<ref>http://175.45.179.68/English/Political/HomeNews%5Cnews10275.htm {{dead link|date=September 2013}}</ref> the country's [[Rubber stamp (politics)|rubber-stamp]] parliament.\n\n==Professor of Citizenship==\nIn 1997, Alton was appointed Professor of Citizenship at [[Liverpool John Moores University]], establishing the Foundation for Citizenship and the Roscoe Lectures.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Foundation for Citizenship: Contacts|url=http://www.ljmu.ac.uk/roscoelectures/97598.htm|date=28 September 2012|publisher=[[Liverpool John Moores University]]|accessdate=14 October 2012}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The lecture series explores citizenship and lectures have been given by commentators including the [[14th Dalai Lama]] and [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Previous lectures and audio downloads|url=http://www.ljmu.ac.uk/roscoelectures/101110.htm|date=5 October 2012|publisher=[[Liverpool John Moores University]]|accessdate=14 October 2012}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Human rights==\nLord Alton established the lobby group for human rights, [[Jubilee Campaign]], in 1987, with the support of other members of parliament. He also co-founded Jubilee Action, a children's charity established to fulfil the humanitarian needs highlighted by the work of Jubilee Campaign. In 2014 Jubilee Action changed its name to Chance for Childhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chanceforchildhood.org/latest-news/announcing-our-new-name-chance-for-childhood/|title=Announcing our new name \u2013 'Chance for Childhood' \u2013 Chance for Childhood \u2013 Children's charity|work=Chance for Childhood,.}}</ref>\n\nLord Alton campaigned against the [[Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 2008]], opposing the creation and use of animal-human hybrid stem cells for medical purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/lord_alton/index.html|title=Comment \u2013 ConservativeHome|publisher=blogs.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he spoke out against the [[British Olympic Association]] when it forced athletes to sign an agreement forbidding them from criticising China's human rights record before or during the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Draper|first1=Rob|last2=King|first2=Daniel|title=Britain kow tows to China as athletes are forced to sign no criticism contracts|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-513362/Britain-kow-tows-China-athletes-forced-sign-criticism-contracts.html|date=10 February 2008|work=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe is a patron of the International Young Leaders Network<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iyln.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828200122/http://www.iyln.com/ |archivedate=28 August 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Save the Congo!, a small international rights group founded by the Congolese rights activist Vava Tampa to end the political crisis that continues to give rise to wars, conflicts and violence that have killed over 5.4 million people in Congo.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=74gZhJOSvxI&t=49s</ref>\n\n===Support for Hong Kong protest movement===\nLord Alton has been unreserved in his support for the [[2019 Hong Kong protests|Hong Kong protests of 2019]].  In reaction to pro-Beijing lawmaker [[Junius Ho]]'s attacks on women and the LGBT+ community, as well as his alleged support of the [[2019 Yuen Long attack|Yuen Long attackers]], Alton wrote to [[Anglia Ruskin University]] urged rescinding the honorary doctoral degree it had conferred on Ho.  The degree was withdrawn on 29 October of that year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E8%A2%AB%E6%96%A5-%E6%93%8D%E5%AE%88%E5%BC%95%E8%B5%B7%E9%97%9C%E6%B3%A8-%E4%BD%95%E5%90%9B%E5%A0%AF%E9%81%AD%E6%AF%8D%E6%A0%A1%E8%A4%AB%E5%A5%AA%E6%A6%AE%E8%AD%BD%E5%8D%9A%E5%A3%AB%E5%AD%B8%E4%BD%8D/|title=\u88ab\u65a5\u300c\u64cd\u5b88\u5f15\u8d77\u95dc\u6ce8\u300d\u3000\u4f55\u541b\u582f\u906d\u6bcd\u6821\u892b\u596a\u540d\u8b7d\u6cd5\u5b78\u535a\u58eb\u5b78\u4f4d|date=2019-10-29|accessdate=2019-10-29|publisher=\u7acb\u5834\u65b0\u805e}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1488726-20191029.htm|title=\u82f1\u570b\u5b89\u683c\u91cc\u4e9e\u9b6f\u65af\u91d1\u5927\u5b78\u892b\u596a\u4f55\u541b\u582f\u540d\u8b7d\u535a\u58eb\u5b78\u4f4d|date=2019-10-29|publisher=\u9999\u6e2f\u96fb\u53f0}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 Hong Kong Polytechnic University conflict]], he issued a statement calling for the end to police violence and roundly criticising Chief Executive Carrie Lam for acting as a Beijing puppet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E7%BE%8E%E8%8B%B1%E5%9C%8B%E6%9C%83%E8%AD%B0%E5%93%A1%E5%91%BC%E7%B1%B2%E6%9E%97%E9%84%AD%E6%8C%87%E4%BB%A4%E8%AD%A6%E6%96%B9%E5%85%8B%E5%88%B6-%E9%98%BB%E6%AD%A2%E5%B1%A0%E6%AE%BA%E7%99%BC%E7%94%9F/|title=\u7f8e\u82f1\u570b\u6703\u8b70\u54e1\u547c\u7c72\u6797\u912d\u6307\u4ee4\u8b66\u65b9\u514b\u5236\u3000\u963b\u6b62\u5c60\u6bba\u767c\u751f|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and arms==\nAlton has been appointed to two Roman Catholic orders of chivalry; he is a Knight Commander of Merit of the [[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George]] (2003) and a Knight Commander of the [[Order of St. Gregory the Great]] (2008).<ref>{{cite web|title=Alton of Liverpool, Baron|url=http://ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U5392/ALTON_OF_LIVERPOOL|work=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=December 2011|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Gules a dove descending Argent a bordure engrailed of twelve points terminating alternately in trefoils and Maltese crosses.\n|crest = An ankh Gules pendant from the crossbar two bells Or.\n|supporters = On either side a Liverbird wings elevated and addorsed Gules legged and in the beak Or a lily Argent slipped and leaved Or.\n|motto = Choose Life <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAlton is married, has four children and two grandchildren, and holds both British and Irish citizenship. He resides in [[Lancashire]], UK and is a Roman Catholic.<ref name=\"davidalton.about\"/><ref name=\"CatholicHerald1\">{{cite web|title='Westminster and Brussels politicians to blame for Brexit vote,' says Catholic peer|url=http://catholicherald.co.uk/news/2016/06/28/westminster-and-brussels-politicians-to-blame-for-brexit-vote-says-catholic-peer/|website=[[Catholic Herald]]|accessdate=19 April 2018|language=en|date=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NCR1\">{{cite web|last1=Frawley Desmond|first1=Joan|title=Lord Alton: 'Never Forget Who You Are'|url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/lord-altons-passions|website=[[National Catholic Register]]|accessdate=19 April 2018|language=en|date=9 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Universe1\">{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Nick|title=Catholic peer urges calm words to heal toxic UK-Russian relations|url=https://www.thecatholicuniverse.com/catholic-peer-urges-calm-words-heal-toxic-uk-russian-relations-16260|website=[[The Universe (Catholic newspaper)|The Universe]]|accessdate=19 April 2018|date=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nLord Alton has published numerous non-fiction titles:\n* ''What Kind of Country?'' Marshall Pickering 1987\n* ''Whose choice anyway?'' Marshal Pickering 1988\n* ''Faith in Britain'' Hodder & Stoughton 1991\n* ''Signs of Contradiction'' Hodder & Stoughton 1996\n* ''Life After Death'' Christian Democrat Press 1997\n* ''Citizen Virtues'' Harper Collins 1999\n* ''Citizen 21'' Harper Collins 2001\n* ''Pilgrim Ways'' St Pauls Publishing 2001\n* ''Passion and Pain'' (with Michele Lombardo) and accompanying DVD of TV series 2003\n* ''Euthanasia: Getting To The Heart of The Matter'' (with Martin Foley) 2005\n* ''Abortion: Getting To The Heart of The Matter'' (with Martin Foley) 2005\n* ''Building Bridges: Is there Hope for North Korea?'' (with [[Rob Chidley]]) Lion 2013\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.davidalton.net/ Lord Alton of Liverpool] official site\n* [https://www.facebook.com/LordAltonofLiverpool/ David Alton] official Facebook page\n* {{UK Peer links | parliament = david-alton/26959 | hansard = mr-david-alton | hansardcurr = 3643 | guardian = | publicwhip = Lord_Alton_of_Liverpool | theywork = lord_alton_of_liverpool | record = David-Alton/1429 | bbc = 26959.stm | journalisted = }}\n* [http://www.jubileecampaign.co.uk/ Jubilee Campaign]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061205034424/http://jubileeaction.co.uk/ Jubilee Action]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par | uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Arthur Irvine|Sir Arthur Irvine]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Liverpool Edge Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Edge Hill]]\n        | years  = [[1979 Liverpool Edge Hill by-election|1979]]\u2013[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished}}\n\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Liverpool Mossley Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Mossley Hill]]\n        | years  = [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished}}\n\n{{s-bef | before = [[Andrew MacKay]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Baby of the House]]\n        | years  = 1979}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Stephen Dorrell]]}}\n\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Alan Beith]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Liberal Chief Whip]]\n        | years  = 1985\u20131987}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness|Jim Wallace]]}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Renton|The Lord Renton of Mount Harry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron Alton of Liverpool'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Douglas Hurd|The Lord Hurd of Westwell]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Babies of the House}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alton, David}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Liverpool Hope University]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers|Alton of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of Merit of the Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Gregory the Great]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Liverpool constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by John Major]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Alton of Liverpool\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of Saint Gregory the Great|KCSG]] [[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George|KCMCO]]\n| image= Official portrait of Lord Alton of Liverpool crop 2, 2019.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| office1 = [[Member of the House of Lords]] <br>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start1 = 17 June 1997<br />[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| term_end1 =\n| office = [[Liberal Chief Whip]]\n| term_start = 1985\n| term_end = 11 June 1987\n| leader = [[David Steel]]\n| preceded = [[Alan Beith]]\n| succeeded = [[Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness|Jim Wallace]]\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Liverpool Mossley Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Mossley Hill]]<br /><small>[[Liverpool Edge Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Edge Hill]] (1979\u20131983)</small>\n| term_start3 = 30 March 1979\n| term_end3 = 1 May 1997\n| predecessor3 = [[Arthur Irvine|Sir Arthur Irvine]]\n| successor3 = ''Constituency abolished''\n| birthname = David Patrick Paul Alton\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|3|15}}\n| birth_place = London\n| party = None ([[Crossbencher|Crossbench]])\n| otherparty = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] (1972\u20131988)<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] (1988\u20131997)\n| alma_mater = [[Liverpool Hope University]]\n| spouse = Elizabeth Bell\n| children = 4\n}}\n'''David Patrick Paul Alton, Baron Alton of Liverpool''', [[Order of Saint Gregory the Great|KCSG]], [[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George|KCMCO]] (born 15 March 1951) is a British politician.\n\nHe is a former [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] and later [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] Member of Parliament who has sat as a [[Crossbencher|crossbench]] member of the [[House of Lords]] since 1997 when he was made a [[life peer]]. A [[Catholic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/why-michael-heseltine-is-like-a-hamster-1621398.html|title=Why Michael Heseltine is like a hamster|work=The Independent|date=28 May 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aJ3CQTnZHoVc&refer=uk|title=First Human-Animal Embryos in U.K. Bring Opposition (Update1)|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/29/weekinreview/ideas-trends-just-what-politicians-needed-a-patron-saint.html?pagewanted=2&src=pm The New York Times]</ref> he has advanced [[anti-abortion]] causes. Alton is also known for his human rights work including the co-founding of Jubilee Action, the children's charity (which changed its name to Chance for Childhood in 2014), and serves as chair, patron or trustee of several charities and voluntary organisations.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.jesuit.org.uk/creative-bridge-between-past-and-present |title = Creative bridge between the past and present &#124; Jesuits in Britain}}</ref>\n\n==Education and entry into politics==\nBorn in London on 15 March 1951,<ref name=\"THE\">{{cite web|title=In the news: David Alton|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=156736|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|date=26 January 2001|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Alton of Liverpool|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/26959.stm|work=Democracy Live|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> His father was a [[7th Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|Desert Rat]] who had served in the [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]], and then worked for the Ford Motor Company. His mother was a native Irish speaker from the West of Ireland. After being rehoused from the East End, Alton was brought up in a council flat on an overspill council estate. He passed a scholarship exam to join the first intake of a new Jesuit grammar school and was educated at the [[Campion School, Hornchurch]], Essex, and [[Liverpool Hope University|Christ's College of Education, Liverpool]].<ref name=\"THE\" /><ref name=\"davidalton.about\">{{Cite web | url=https://davidalton.net/about/ |title = About|date = 12 December 2010}}</ref> He began his career as a teacher and, in 1972, he was elected as a Liberal to [[Liverpool City Council]] as Britain's youngest city councillor. Alton was elected for the Low Hill ward, serving from 1972 to 1974, then, after the Local Government Act 1974, he was elected for the Smithdown ward where he served for the next six years. Ashton was also a member of [[Merseyside County Council]] for the Smithdown division from 1974 to 1977 and chairman of the housing committee. He was deputy leader of Liverpool City Council from 1975 to 1978.<ref name=\"davidalton.about\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nAlton was elected as Member of Parliament for [[Liverpool Edge Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Edge Hill]] at a [[1979 Liverpool Edge Hill by-election|by-election in 1979]] for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], when he became the \"[[Baby of the House]]\". achieving a record swing of 36.8% and 64% of the vote. He won the seat the day after the Callaghan Government was defeated in a vote of confidence and the 1979 General Election being called. He became the shortest lived MP, a member for less than a week, and made his Maiden Speech within three hours of taking his seat. Five weeks later he was re-elected and went on to serve as a Liverpool MP for 18 years, before standing down. He was the only new member of a Parliamentary Party of 11 MPs.  He campaigned on the slogan \u201cEveryone Knows Someone Who Has Been Helped by David Alton.\u201d<ref name=\"davidalton.about\"/> He was notably a very short-serving Baby of the House, as [[Stephen Dorrell]], who was a year younger than Alton, was elected at the 1979 election.\n\n[[File:DA - Everone knows someone.jpg|thumb|left|David Alton and his 1979 by-election campaign poster]]\n\nWhen the Edge Hill constituency was abolished for the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]], he was elected to represent the new [[Liverpool Mossley Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Mossley Hill]] constituency.\n\nFrom 1979 to 1988 he served at various times as spokesman on the environment, home affairs, Northern Ireland and as [[Chief Whip]]. He is known for his strongly [[anti-abortion]] position, and in 1987 he resigned as Chief Whip to campaign for his unsuccessful [[private member's bill]] which aimed to stop late abortions. He became a [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] MP when the Liberal Party merged with the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]] in 1988, but he had difficult relations with parts of the party, especially over attempts to make the party adopt a position [[Abortion-rights movements|in favor of abortion rights]]. In 1992, he announced that he would not stand again as a Liberal Democrat after the party passed a policy that he believed committed the party to support abortion for the first time.  A motion passed in Spring 1993 stating that the party had no position on the substantive issue of abortion spared him delivering on the promise.\n\nHe stood down as an MP at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. He was made a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Alton of Liverpool''', of [[Mossley Hill]] in the County of Merseyside<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54743 |date=18 April 1997 |page=4707 |supp=y }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54809 |date=17 June 1997 |page=7011 }}</ref> as a personal choice of [[John Major]] in the [[Dissolution Honours]], and took his seat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[crossbencher]].\n\nLord Alton is chairman of the British-DPRK All-Party Parliamentary Group, and visited Pyongyang in October 2010<ref>http://175.45.179.68/English/Political/HomeNews%5Cnews10263.htm {{dead link|date=September 2013}}</ref> when he had talks with leaders of the North Korean government including Choe Thae Bok, chairman of the [[Supreme People's Assembly]],<ref>http://175.45.179.68/English/Political/HomeNews%5Cnews10275.htm {{dead link|date=September 2013}}</ref> the country's [[Rubber stamp (politics)|rubber-stamp]] parliament.\n\n==Professor of Citizenship==\nIn 1997, Alton was appointed Professor of Citizenship at [[Liverpool John Moores University]], establishing the Foundation for Citizenship and the Roscoe Lectures.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Foundation for Citizenship: Contacts|url=http://www.ljmu.ac.uk/roscoelectures/97598.htm|date=28 September 2012|publisher=[[Liverpool John Moores University]]|accessdate=14 October 2012}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The lecture series explores citizenship and lectures have been given by commentators including the [[14th Dalai Lama]] and [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Previous lectures and audio downloads|url=http://www.ljmu.ac.uk/roscoelectures/101110.htm|date=5 October 2012|publisher=[[Liverpool John Moores University]]|accessdate=14 October 2012}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Human rights==\nLord Alton established the lobby group for human rights, [[Jubilee Campaign]], in 1987, with the support of other members of parliament. He also co-founded Jubilee Action, a children's charity established to fulfil the humanitarian needs highlighted by the work of Jubilee Campaign. In 2014 Jubilee Action changed its name to Chance for Childhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chanceforchildhood.org/latest-news/announcing-our-new-name-chance-for-childhood/|title=Announcing our new name \u2013 'Chance for Childhood' \u2013 Chance for Childhood \u2013 Children's charity|work=Chance for Childhood,.}}</ref>\n\nLord Alton campaigned against the [[Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 2008]], opposing the creation and use of animal-human hybrid stem cells for medical purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/lord_alton/index.html|title=Comment \u2013 ConservativeHome|publisher=blogs.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he spoke out against the [[British Olympic Association]] when it forced athletes to sign an agreement forbidding them from criticising China's human rights record before or during the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Draper|first1=Rob|last2=King|first2=Daniel|title=Britain kow tows to China as athletes are forced to sign no criticism contracts|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-513362/Britain-kow-tows-China-athletes-forced-sign-criticism-contracts.html|date=10 February 2008|work=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe is a patron of the International Young Leaders Network<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iyln.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828200122/http://www.iyln.com/ |archivedate=28 August 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Save the Congo!, a small international rights group founded by the Congolese rights activist Vava Tampa to end the political crisis that continues to give rise to wars, conflicts and violence that have killed over 5.4 million people in Congo.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=74gZhJOSvxI&t=49s</ref>\n\n===Support for Hong Kong protest movement===\nLord Alton has been unreserved in his support for the [[2019 Hong Kong protests|Hong Kong protests of 2019]].  In reaction to pro-Beijing lawmaker [[Junius Ho]]'s attacks on women and the LGBT+ community, as well as his alleged support of the [[2019 Yuen Long attack|Yuen Long attackers]], Alton wrote to [[Anglia Ruskin University]] urged rescinding the honorary doctoral degree it had conferred on Ho.  The degree was withdrawn on 29 October of that year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E8%A2%AB%E6%96%A5-%E6%93%8D%E5%AE%88%E5%BC%95%E8%B5%B7%E9%97%9C%E6%B3%A8-%E4%BD%95%E5%90%9B%E5%A0%AF%E9%81%AD%E6%AF%8D%E6%A0%A1%E8%A4%AB%E5%A5%AA%E6%A6%AE%E8%AD%BD%E5%8D%9A%E5%A3%AB%E5%AD%B8%E4%BD%8D/|title=\u88ab\u65a5\u300c\u64cd\u5b88\u5f15\u8d77\u95dc\u6ce8\u300d\u3000\u4f55\u541b\u582f\u906d\u6bcd\u6821\u892b\u596a\u540d\u8b7d\u6cd5\u5b78\u535a\u58eb\u5b78\u4f4d|date=2019-10-29|accessdate=2019-10-29|publisher=\u7acb\u5834\u65b0\u805e}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1488726-20191029.htm|title=\u82f1\u570b\u5b89\u683c\u91cc\u4e9e\u9b6f\u65af\u91d1\u5927\u5b78\u892b\u596a\u4f55\u541b\u582f\u540d\u8b7d\u535a\u58eb\u5b78\u4f4d|date=2019-10-29|publisher=\u9999\u6e2f\u96fb\u53f0}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 Hong Kong Polytechnic University conflict]], he issued a statement calling for the end to police violence and roundly criticising Chief Executive Carrie Lam for acting as a Beijing puppet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E7%BE%8E%E8%8B%B1%E5%9C%8B%E6%9C%83%E8%AD%B0%E5%93%A1%E5%91%BC%E7%B1%B2%E6%9E%97%E9%84%AD%E6%8C%87%E4%BB%A4%E8%AD%A6%E6%96%B9%E5%85%8B%E5%88%B6-%E9%98%BB%E6%AD%A2%E5%B1%A0%E6%AE%BA%E7%99%BC%E7%94%9F/|title=\u7f8e\u82f1\u570b\u6703\u8b70\u54e1\u547c\u7c72\u6797\u912d\u6307\u4ee4\u8b66\u65b9\u514b\u5236\u3000\u963b\u6b62\u5c60\u6bba\u767c\u751f|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and arms==\nAlton has been appointed to two Roman Catholic orders of chivalry; he is a Knight Commander of Merit of the [[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George]] (2003) and a Knight Commander of the [[Order of St. Gregory the Great]] (2008).<ref>{{cite web|title=Alton of Liverpool, Baron|url=http://ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U5392/ALTON_OF_LIVERPOOL|work=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=December 2011|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Gules a dove descending Argent a bordure engrailed of twelve points terminating alternately in trefoils and Maltese crosses.\n|crest = An ankh Gules pendant from the crossbar two bells Or.\n|supporters = On either side a Liverbird wings elevated and addorsed Gules legged and in the beak Or a lily Argent slipped and leaved Or.\n|motto = Choose Life <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAlton is married, has four children and two grandchildren, and holds both British and Irish citizenship. He resides in [[Lancashire]], UK and is a Roman Catholic.<ref name=\"davidalton.about\"/><ref name=\"CatholicHerald1\">{{cite web|title='Westminster and Brussels politicians to blame for Brexit vote,' says Catholic peer|url=http://catholicherald.co.uk/news/2016/06/28/westminster-and-brussels-politicians-to-blame-for-brexit-vote-says-catholic-peer/|website=[[Catholic Herald]]|accessdate=19 April 2018|language=en|date=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NCR1\">{{cite web|last1=Frawley Desmond|first1=Joan|title=Lord Alton: 'Never Forget Who You Are'|url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/lord-altons-passions|website=[[National Catholic Register]]|accessdate=19 April 2018|language=en|date=9 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Universe1\">{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Nick|title=Catholic peer urges calm words to heal toxic UK-Russian relations|url=https://www.thecatholicuniverse.com/catholic-peer-urges-calm-words-heal-toxic-uk-russian-relations-16260|website=[[The Universe (Catholic newspaper)|The Universe]]|accessdate=19 April 2018|date=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nLord Alton has published numerous non-fiction titles:\n* ''What Kind of Country?'' Marshall Pickering 1987\n* ''Whose choice anyway?'' Marshal Pickering 1988\n* ''Faith in Britain'' Hodder & Stoughton 1991\n* ''Signs of Contradiction'' Hodder & Stoughton 1996\n* ''Life After Death'' Christian Democrat Press 1997\n* ''Citizen Virtues'' Harper Collins 1999\n* ''Citizen 21'' Harper Collins 2001\n* ''Pilgrim Ways'' St Pauls Publishing 2001\n* ''Passion and Pain'' (with Michele Lombardo) and accompanying DVD of TV series 2003\n* ''Euthanasia: Getting To The Heart of The Matter'' (with Martin Foley) 2005\n* ''Abortion: Getting To The Heart of The Matter'' (with Martin Foley) 2005\n* ''Building Bridges: Is there Hope for North Korea?'' (with [[Rob Chidley]]) Lion 2013\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.davidalton.net/ Lord Alton of Liverpool] official site\n* [https://www.facebook.com/LordAltonofLiverpool/ David Alton] official Facebook page\n* {{UK Peer links | parliament = david-alton/26959 | hansard = mr-david-alton | hansardcurr = 3643 | guardia